                "protocols": [
                    {
                        "comments": [],
                        "name": "Sample collection",
                        "protocolType": {
                            "comments": [],
                            "annotationValue": "Sample collection",
                            "termSource": null,
                            "termAccession": ""
                        },
                        "description": "<p>In May 2021, mature hypocotyls of <em>Kandelia obovata</em> were collected from Quanzhou Bay Luoyang River Mangrove Nature Reserve (24\u00b059\u2019N, 118\u00b059\u2019E) in Quanzhou City, Fujian Province and Longgang Aojiangkou Mangrove (28\u00b012\u2019N,120\u00b096\u2019E) in Wenzhou City, Zhejiang Province. Healthy and mature hypocotyls of similar size without any diseases or pests were carefully selected and transplanted into plastic pots at the Nanhui Dongtan Mangrove Base (30\u00b090\u2032N, 121\u00b097\u2032E) in Shanghai. After a growth period of 19 months, in December 2022, a total of 50 healthy and homogeneous <em>K. obovata</em> seedlings were individually chosen from each population, Quanzhou in Fujian (F-J) and Wenzhou in Zhejiang (Z-J), respectively. These seedlings were subsequently placed in incubators for cold stress treatment and sampling, with a photoperiod set at 16 h per day and humidity maintained at 40%. Cold treatment conditions are T1 (8 \u00b0C) \u2192 T2 (4 \u00b0C) \u2192 T3 (0 \u00b0C) \u2192 T4 (-4 \u00b0C) \u2192 T5 (0 \u00b0C) \u2192 T6 (4 \u00b0C).The second mature leaf at stages T1-T6 was collected from the F-J and Z-J populations. Each time point comprised of 6 biological replicates, resulting in a total of 72 samples.</p>",
                        "uri": "",
                        "version": "",
                        "parameters": [
                            {
                                "comments": [],
                                "parameterName": {
                                    "comments": [],
                                    "annotationValue": "",
                                    "termSource": null,
                                    "termAccession": ""
                                }
                            }
                        ],
                        "components": []
                    },
                    {
                        "comments": [],
                        "name": "Extraction",
                        "protocolType": {
                            "comments": [],
                            "annotationValue": "Extraction",
                            "termSource": null,
                            "termAccession": ""
                        },
                        "description": "<p>Briefly, 50 mg solid sample were accurately weighed, and the metabolites were extracted using a 400 \u00b5L methanol:water (4:1, v/v) solution with 0.02 mg/mL of L-2-chlorophenylalanin as internal standard. The mixture was allowed to settle at -10 \u00b0C and treated with a Wonbio-96c High-Throughput Tissue Crusher (Shanghai Wanbai Biotechnology Co., Ltd) at 50 Hz for 6 min, then followed by ultrasound at 40 kHz for 30 min at 5 \u00b0C. The samples were placed at -20 \u00b0C for 30 min to precipitate proteins. After centrifugation at 13,000 x g at 4 \u00b0C for 15 min, the supernatant were carefully transferred to sample vials for LC-MS/MS analysis.</p><p><br></p><p>Pooled QC samples were prepared by mixing equal volumes of all 72 individual samples. These QC samples underwent the same processing and testing procedures as the analytic samples, ensuring their representativeness of the entire sample set. QCs were injected at regular intervals (every 10 samples) to monitor the stability and reproducibility of the analysis. For 72 metabolome samples, approximately 7 QC samples were generated (QC01-QC07).</p>",
                        "uri": "",
                        "version": "",
                        "parameters": [
                            {
                                "comments": [],
                                "parameterName": {
                                    "comments": [],
                                    "annotationValue": "Post Extraction",
                                    "termSource": null,
                                    "termAccession": ""
                                }
                            },
                            {
                                "comments": [],
                                "parameterName": {
                                    "comments": [],
                                    "annotationValue": "Derivatization",
                                    "termSource": null,
                                    "termAccession": ""
                                }
                            }
                        ],
                        "components": []
                    },
                    {
                        "comments": [],
                        "name": "Chromatography",
                        "protocolType": {
                            "comments": [],
                            "annotationValue": "Chromatography",
                            "termSource": null,
                            "termAccession": ""
                        },
                        "description": "<p>Analysis of the samples was performed using a <strong>Thermo Scientific Vanquish Horizon UHPLC System </strong>and an <strong>ACQUITY UPLC HSS T3 (1.8 \u00b5m, 2.1 mm x 100 mm; Waters)</strong> column. The mobile phases consisted of 0.1% formic acid in water:acetonitrile (95:5, v/v) (solvent A) and 0.1% formic acid in acetonitrile:isopropanol:water (47.5:47.5:5, v/v) (solvent B). The solvent gradient changed according to the following conditions: from 0.0 to 3.5 min, from 0% B to 24.5% B (0.4 mL/min); from 3.5 to 5.0 min, from 24.5% B to 65% B (0.4 mL/min); from 5.0 to 5.5 min, from 65% B to 100% B (0.4 mL/min); from 5.5 to 7.4 min, from 100% B to 100% B (0.4 mL/min to 0.6 mL/min); from 7.4 to 7.6 min, from 100% B to 51.5% B (0.6 mL/min); from 7.6 to 7.8 min, from 51.5% B to 0% B (0.6 mL/min to 0.5 mL/min); from 7.8 to 9.0 min, from 0% B to 0% B (0.5 mL/min to 0.4 mL/min); from 9.0 to 10.0 min, from 0% B to 0% B (0.4 mL/min) for equilibrating the systems. The sample injection volume was 2 \u00b5L and the flow rate was set to 0.4 mL/min. The column temperature was maintained at 40 \u00b0C. During the period of analysis, all these samples were stored at 4 \u00b0C.</p>",
